	<div id="p136781" class="post bg1">
		<div class="inner"><span class="corners-top"><span></span></span>

		<div class="postbody">
			

			<h3 ><a href="#p136781"></a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=136781#p136781"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=776">brakeformezz</a></strong> &raquo; Dec 2nd, '07, 22:24 </p>

			

			<div class="content">Interesting opening statement in that article:
<br />
<br /><blockquote class="uncited"><div>TV licence payers should demand the right to keep indefinitely the programmes they download - just as they can keep content recorded on VCRs</div></blockquote>
<br />
<br />Since people don't pay the content creator to make a VCR recording, I'm not sure VCRs are the best comparison. The reasoning that VCR manufacturers don't controbute to copyright infringement relies upon the fact that most VCR recordings are so the owner can view a show at a different time, not keep it indefinitely. And I imagine most people still do that, who don't own TiVo. They tape the shows they miss when they went on vacation or had to work late or whatever, then catch up and probably tape over it later.
<br />
<br />Anyway, I think what consumers are willing to pay for should dictate what licenses are offered. Maybe they could offer the option of a permanent license for extra. Pay the basic rate for a 28 day viewing period, and if you want to keep something forever you pay an extra $20 or whatever.
<br />
<br />But they're not offering that right now, so this is what consumers have to take or leave. This isn't drinking water we're talking about, it's television and there are lots of ways to view shows, not to mention alternatives that gel your brain just as well. If somebody doesn't like the 28 day window and wants to have a permanent copy, then they can not get the service and wait for their Doctor Who episodes to come out on DVD.</div>

			

		</div>

		
